Well, all the people that posted replies had good ideas, but there's also
this one.....

You have a wreck, and then there's this *little tiny spark* under the hood
there, and now you're kinda sideways, and the ignition is still on, and the
pump is still pumping twenty five gallons of gas all over you cause the key
is still on, and you can't turn it off for some reason.....

You should wire your fuel pump through a relay that is controlled by the
output/charging wire on your alternator. When the engine stops, the
alternator stops turning, so it stops charging the battery, and the charging
wire looses current, and so shuts off the fuel. Either that or you might be
able to use a tach lead.

Then also, you'd need to wire a switch in that bypasses the relay, so that
you could run the fuel pump by the switch to prime the car for starting
(if the alternator runs the relay, you won't have current till after the
engine starts) , or to test the system, or for other possible needs......

Virtually all modern cars are set up to where if the engine stops so does
the fuel pump. But they have one relay that primes as well as runs the pump,
as well as capabilities to run the pump manually if you want to. One relay
does all the above.

So, however you do it, use a relay......

